content.text:
The issue was caused by `WrappingRule` incorrectly calculating the line length when a code block is inside a multi-line string template (like a raw string). When determining the start and end of the current line to check against `max_line_length`, the rule used `isWhiteSpaceWithNewline()` to find the line boundaries. However, multi-line string literals (e.g., `"""..."""`) are not whitespace, so the traversal would skip over the entire multi-line string content, effectively concatenating multiple lines of the raw string with the current line. This resulted in a very large calculated line length, triggering the wrapping rule incorrectly.

I fixed this by updating the `startOfLine` and `endOfLine` search logic in `WrappingRule.kt` to stop when encountering any node that contains a newline character (`textContains('\n')`), not just whitespace nodes. I also updated the line length calculation to correctly handle the text segments before/after the newline within such nodes.

# file: ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/WrappingRule.kt
```kotlin
                maxLineLength > 0 -> {
                    val startOfLine = node.prevLeaf { it.isWhiteSpaceWithNewline() || it.textContains('\n') }
                    val endOfLine = node.nextLeaf { it.isWhiteSpaceWithNewline() || it.textContains('\n') }
                    val line =
                        startOfLine
                            ?.leaves()
                            ?.takeWhile { it != endOfLine }
                            ?.joinToString(separator = "") { it.text }
                            ?.substringAfterLast('\n')
                            .orEmpty()
                    val endText = endOfLine?.text?.substringBefore('\n') ?: ""
                    (line.length + endText.length) > maxLineLength
                }
